'''Nagios''' offers complete monitoring and alerting for servers, switches, applications, and services.

== Install Nagios ==
Decide whether you want to use lighttpd or apache2 as the nagios frontend, and enable the preferred webserver USE flag for nagios.

{{RootCmd|<pre>USE="exif gd truetype" emerge apache2  (Required to specify "gd" USE flag, else emerge is blocked)</pre>}}
{{RootCmd|<pre>USE="nagios-ping nagios-ssh" emerge net-analyzer/nagios-plugins (Some preferred plugins)</pre>}}
{{RootCmd|<pre>USE="apache2" emerge net-analyzer/nagios-core</pre>}}

== Apache Web Server Configuration ==
Follow the instructions within the PHP Gentoo Wiki.

You'll need to enable the NAGIOS and PHP modules and test PHP works.

{{File|/etc/conf.d/apache2||<pre>
APACHE2_OPTS="-D DEFAULT_VHOST -D INFO -D SSL -D SSL_DEFAULT_VHOST -D LANGUAGE -D NAGIOS -D PHP5"</pre>}}

== Specify Allowed Users ==
Edit the /etc/groups file and add the user name(s) to the nagios group, whom are allowed access to the Nagios service.

Once done, completely log-out from all shells and relogin for the update to /etc/groups to occur.

== Start the Services ==
{{RootCmd|rc-update add nagios default}}
{{RootCmd|rc-update add apache2 default}}

{{RootCmd|rc-service nagios start}}
{{RootCmd|rc-service apache2 start}}

== Navigate to the Nagios Web Page ==
Open your browser and navigate to "http://localhost/nagios"
